  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering and Financial Crimes Strategy Act\n\n2. Key provisions:\n- Criminalize financial transactions intended to conceal illegally obtained money\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Impose reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\n3. Enforcement agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n4. International cooperation:\n- Many countries have similar anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards\n\n5. Penalties:\n- Criminal penalties can include:\n  - Substantial fines\n  - Prison sentences\n  - Asset forfeiture\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the concealment of illegally obtained funds.",
